          "body": "The doxology of 1:17 closes the autobiographical excursus with a deliberately Old Testament-shaped praise — *King eternal, immortal, invisible, the only God* (echoing Deut 6:4, Ps 145, Isa 40). Then Paul resumes the charge: Timothy is to *fight the good fight* (1:18) *keeping faith and a good conscience* (1:19). The pairing is the chapter's pastoral payoff. Doctrine (faith) and ethics (conscience) cannot be divorced. Reject the conscience and the faith founders — Paul names the metaphor *shipwreck* (*nauageo*, 1:19), a verb Paul knew literally (2 Cor 11:25). Hymenaeus (cf. 2 Tim 2:17) and Alexander are not hypothetical case studies; they are named men handed over to Satan (an exclusion from the protective sphere of the church, cf. 1 Cor 5:5) for the redemptive purpose that they may be *taught* (*paideuo*, disciplined) not to blaspheme. Church discipline in this chapter is restorative, not punitive."
